item.title: 2016 New Years Project
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Every year I challenge myself to a project. It's my New Years-ish resolution. My way of exercising the creative side of my brain. My way of documenting life. However, halfway through each year I often wonder why I signed myself up for this! Yet as I begin to put the pieces of my project together at the end of each year I am always thankful for the choice I made. 2016 was one of my hardest projects yet and will be one of my most cherished projects. A short one second video everyday in 2016. It's the small, simple everyday moments, I never want to forget. https://vimeo.com/197803537 password: hawks While I'm still deciding on my 2017 challenge, the consistent theme will definitely be - RECORD.

item.title: walk through california
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Mitchell's class participated in a Walk Through California program. Each student in the class was asked to memorize two expert words and participate in the fun by coming in costume. Mitch partnered with Mark to build a jail for his "gold thief" costume. He received lots of comments from his teachers and classmates and was very proud of the thought and creativity that went into his costume. I was able to attend half of the Walk through California presentation and was very impressed. The kids were split into teams and the session was very interactive the entire time requiring them to present their expert words along the way. The presentation started when the Native Americans arrived in California and the story worked its way forward through the different changes of power to today. There were different characters and challenges the kids participated in to challenge them and show their knowledge, which they loved. Mitch was chosen to reenact the time Spain was in power and did a great job with his acting! What lucky kids to be able to sit through this program with their class...

item.title: happy birthday mitchy
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Dear Mitchy, Wow! We did it! 10 years! Happy Birthday Buddy. I am so very proud that you’re my son. And as in years past I thought I'd celebrate your birthday and our decade together with a little note - 10 years ago, it was a cold Sunday morning in February, Super Bowl morning, as you know! I convinced your Dad to go on a hike, quite a hilly hike, trying to keep things moving. You see, I was not a patient expectant mom. I was dying to meet you and could not wait any longer. 10 years ago, you came into my world. You changed me completely. You were my 1st first baby. You always will be. Someday when you have children of your own you will comprehend all that that means. Because you are my 1st, that will always mean unchartered territory for me. Sometimes I get it right, often I do not. You and your needs are always at the top of my list. 10 years ago, I could only hope you would sleep another hour. Today, realizing how quickly the past 10 years has sped by before my eyes, it makes me want to take back each and every bedtime story, campfire snuggle, park date, and bike ride and do them all over again. Holding hands with my now 10 year old son feels so fleeting. Like every time you let me hold your hand I wonder if it will be the last. I want you to know how much I love to watch you. I love watching you hike, climb, swim, and explore. I love watching you throw, catch and shoot. Your smile makes your beautiful spirit all the more engaging. Mitchy, you teach me so many things. You make my heart pound so hard I’m afraid it may burst equally with love and pain. You have so much empathy and wonder and oh, so many questions. You think about everything. You have your whole life ahead of you and I have so many dreams and wishes for you. The world is yours for the taking and I want you to grab hold and never let go. I want you to live your life, follow your dreams and never give up. But more importantly, I want you to be true to yourself. Live the life you want to lead, love the things you want to love and do the things you want to do. You only get this one life and if it’s what you truly want to do, know that I will always be there for you and support you all the way. To get there, I encourage you to ‘do your best’, but please don’t confuse that with having to ‘be the best’ because although the words are very similar there lies a great divide between them. Just keep believing in yourself and you’ll always head in the right direction. Please know that as you step away, I am rooting for you. It may feel like I am trying to hold you back, but I am in your corner cheering you on like no one ever will. Happy 10th birthday!  I love you always. Your Momma   Happy 10th year buckie! My buckie, I can't believe that you are already 10 years old. The big double digit! I know for you it seems to have been a long time since you were born, but for me it just seems like yesterday! I will never forget the huge lungs you had (and still have) and what a cuddle bug you are. As I reflect back on your life, I am so proud of what you have become and so excited to see you grow and learn. I love your competitive spirit, you pick up lacrosse and instead of taking it easy, you practice as if this is the lacrosse championship. You approach your audition for the play with the same dedication and effort. This makes me so very very proud. Don't ever stop doing this! As I say when I coach, the two most important things are attitude and effort, keep it up I see both of those in everything you do. Enjoy being a 10 year old. Buckie/Tuckie

item.title: valetines box
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: He knows I'm always up for a good art project. So when the assignment goes out to the class, he comes home and the brainstorming sessions with Mom begins! We talk about ideas, draw sample designs on paper, conversations go on and on and on. We spent Friday night working on our idea but it didn't go as well as well as we had hoped. So while he sat sick on the sofa all Sunday I snuck away for a few minutes and secretly printed off a mini photo of him shooting. I glued the photo on cardboard and taped it to his box. item.title: 10 with friends
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: For Mitchy's birthday we took a few of his friends to the last St Mary's mens basketball game. Lucky for us the Gael's decided to give away shirts and beanies in celebration of Mitch's birthday (or wait, maybe that was for Senior night!?!). The kids were outfitted the entire game and loved it. Over the last few games the boys have created a fan club for a Freshman on the team, Jordan Ford to support and cheer for. They tell us they like his style of play and give him bonus point for resembling one of their favorite football players. The boys make signs and cheer for him at every game, giving their best fan-cheer to get him off the bench and on the court. This game was no different. In the afternoon, before game time Mitch convinced me to take him to the dollar store. He bought 5 signs for each friend so they could hold up a sentence in the stands for this player. During warms ups they stood at the railing holding their signs and were thrilled to receive a wave from their best player! After the game started, two of the boys bumped into Jordan's Mom in the food line. She asked how they knew her son and thanked them for cheering for him. When the boys got back to their seats, word got around about meeting Jordan's Mom. Not soon after, all the boys went on a group hunt to find Jordan's Mom, yelling "Mrs Ford, Mrs Ford? through the stands. Lucky for them, their cries were heard and they found her and asked if they could meet Jordan after the game. She very kindly agreed to help with their request and they were so thrilled they could hardly sit still in their seats. During the last two minutes of the game Jordan was asked to play, after 20 long grueling minutes of the boys cheering and chanting "MVP" from the stands. Many of the fans around us asked who they were cheering for as no one had heard of this player before. The game ended and the boys quickly disappeared to find Jordan's Mom then took formation along the stands in anticipation of his arrival. Finally, their wish came true and Jordan emerged from the locker room, greeted by his biggest local fans. Jordan was so sweet to the boys, signed their signs and t-shirts and took a photo with them. This was the best night for the boys and they all proudly wore their fan gear, coveted their signs and went to bed with big smiles vowing to locate Jordan's youtube channel and become followers. What a fun night, had by all!

item.title: spring break - day 1
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: With a 4th grader and a soon-to-be-fourth grader in the house we decided this was the year to head along the California coast and explore the Missions of California. Road-trippers ready? Lunch stop in Paso Robles. We were hungry and ready to get out and stretch our legs. Good thing the town was so cute, I snuck a bit of shopping in too! We made it - Pismo beach for two nights. We wondered why everyone was leaving the beach at 4pm but quickly realized we were the only silly ones heading straight to the freezing cold coast line late in the day! Crazy kids braved the icy water but it didn't take long for their lips to go blue. Time to head back to the hotel! For a dip in the hot tub and gymnastics on the grass. Beautiful sunset before dinner. Love these two kiddos!

item.title: spring break - day 2
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Next stop, Hearst Castle, Casa del Mar — Spanish for “House of the Sea"— offers breathtaking views of California's pristine Central Coast and the Pacific Ocean. The most formal and elaborately decorated cottage on The Enchanted Hill, Casa del Mar was also where W. R. Hearst spent his last years at the Castle. We opted to tour the Grand Rooms which provided us insight into the main rooms or Castle. Mitchell was a little disappointed the outdoor pool was under construction but are thankful we made it on the bus in time! Away to the Castle we go! Hanging in the indoor pool where we ran into a group of Choir students from a High School on a field trip. It was amazing to hear them sing inside the different rooms.

item.title: spring break - san luis obispo mission
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Mitchell's 4th grade Mission project was on San Luis Obispo so we knew this would be one of our many stops along the way during our Spring Break tour. This was the fifth California mission founded by Father Junipero Serra, Sept. 1, 1772. Named after Saint Louis, Bishop of Toulouse, France. Mitch loved being able to see the Mission grounds. He was quite surprised that the photos and the model he made was a little different from how the Mission looked in person!

item.title: spring break - day 3
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: This was the day to head North along 101, the official California El Camino Real route to explore more of the Missions. We stopped at two Missions along the route to Monterey. First Stop - Mission San Miguel - one of California's historical and cultural treasures. The beautiful old adobe building, whose foundations were laid more than 200 years ago, named for the Archangel Saint Michael - was founded by Franciscan Father Fermin Francisco de Lasuen in 1797, and was meant to close the gap between Mission San Antonio to the north and Mission San Luis Obispo to the south. 2nd Stop - Mission San Antonio de Padua - founded 14 July 1771 by Saint Junipero Serra. The mission is named for Saint Anthony. The mission is largely restored from the rebuilt original. In this photo Mark is teaching the kids how to read a sun dial.

item.title: spring break - day 4
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: We spent the morning of our 4th day on Spring Break riding our bikes along Highway 1. Stopping to watch the waves, searching for crabs and sea stars amongst the tide pools and making our way along the 17 mile drive of Carmel.

item.title: spring break - mission San Carlos Borromeo
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Mission Carmel is the second mission built by Franciscan missionaries in Upper California. It was first established as Mission San Carlos Borromeo in Monterey, California near the native village of Tamo on June 3, 1770. It was named for Carlo Borromeo, Archbishop of Milan, Italy. Matilda decided this was her most favorite Mission and one she wants to study next year. Matilda made it "her mission" to do cartwheels in the courtyard of every Mission!

item.title: spring break - day 5
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Our last and final Mission on this trip was to visit the Mission Santa Cruz. Mission Santa Cruz was a Spanish mission founded by the Franciscan order in present-day Santa Cruz, California. The mission was founded in 1791 and named for the feast of the Exaltation of the Cross, adopting the name given to a nearby creek by the missionary priest Juan Crespi.

item.title: happy birthday matilda
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Matilda - Today you are 9 -- wow, NINE!!!  I can't believe it either but your birth certificate doesn't lie, even if I haven't aged a day past 21. I remember the day you were born like yesterday and yet, some things have changed. You're taller, smarter and more self-sufficient then I could every imagine. You know how to divide, multiply, work an IPad and yesterday you informed us about California and it's many different regions. Watching you grow up has been both exciting, terrifying and has gone far too fast for my liking! In nine more short years, you will be 18 and, as the last nine years has proven, a lot will change. As we enter into the next phase of your life, there are a few things important your Dad and I want you to know - We love you! We often said to you that we're your parents first and your friends second. Our job is to guide you through the tough waters ahead, keep you safe and help you grow into the woman you’re destined to become. Our decisions won’t always be popular with you, we're sure you realize that by now. But, no matter what, we love you unconditionally and nothing, absolutely nothing, will ever change that. You can trust us to always be there to love you, to listen to you, and to be there to share you biggest joys and cry with you through your worst tears. We believe in you. We are your biggest fans, your biggest cheerleaders, your biggest supporters. No matter what you decide to do, we want to be there with you. You are great, you are wonderful. We have so many hopes and dreams for you, but most of all we want you to know that we believe in you. You are special. You are enough, exactly as you are. Love yourself for who you are in this exact moment, because you are perfect. This is a lesson that most of us learn later in life, but we're letting you in on it now. You are a gift to this world, and if you ever forget, just ask. We know we're just your parents, but we have a long list of compelling reasons why you are awesome. Life. Use the right measurements in life. We told your brother and now we are telling you. Life is not measured in the amount of likes you get on Instagram, numbers on a scale or even your GPA. Don’t pretend to be something you’re not. It feels good to fit in and it feels good to be liked, but you will find that being accepted only when you are pretending to be something you’re not is an exhausting, unfulfilling experience. Always remember that life is about the impact you have on others, so work on building your brain and growing your heart, and the rest will fall into place. Failure. Remember that it’s okay to fail. It’s what you do next that matters. Here goes our broken record again. If you never fail, if nothing bad ever happens in your life, if you never have to struggle – then you can never know what it feels like to succeed. Those moments when you have to look deep inside and start fresh are the moments that your drive will lead you to new heights. Remember, your only competition is yourself, so challenge yourself to cross your own personal finish lines!  Your Race. Run your own race. Following some rules is absolutely necessary – like while driving, crossing the street, or paying our taxes. But remember this – always being consistent will not provide a solution to all your problems. You need to train your brain to look around at all possibilities…and to think independently. You don’t need to always follow the leader. You sometimes need to ‘be’ the leader. Decisions. Your decisions are important. One decision can change the trajectory of your life. It takes courage to decide you are not ready for something, and courage to decide to make yourself vulnerable and try something new. Always be courageous. Know that your life and career will start and end with you. Life will provide you with the right tools, resources and opportunities you need to be successful. Then it will be entirely up to you to choose the easy path, or the one less travelled. Us. Yourself, Dad and I have many, many more years of learning together. You will learn so much more in life, and we will learn how to support you through each step. We are thrilled to be your parents! Yes we are, just as you are excited to be Laylah and Woolies Mom, we are so lucky to be your parents, and so lucky to have you as our daughter. Don’t forget this.. We did it, Miss Matilda – we survived the first nine years. Thank you for the lessons, the laughter and changing us forever – you’re our everything. Happy 9th birthday! Love – Mom & Dad (Mitchy & Molly too!)

item.title: life at sea
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today Mitchell's 5th grade class embarks on their required training to set sail in the ocean next week for their overnight field trip on a ship. Today they will practice tying knots, hoisting a flag, rowing a boat, and much much more. The kids all decided to dress up like sailors for the day so last night we got to work with our pens and paper and outfitted Mitch with a custom sailor hat! After I took this picture I told Mitch, "see that lil blue ocean behind you, that's about as far out to sea you're going to go from home". His response, "oh Mom." item.title: Age of sail
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today Mitchy heads out in the high sea. This field trip includes a night spent on a ship in the San Francisco waters. As part of the program the kids will have a chance to get a "mail call" in the evening. Each family was asked to secretly write a letter in the style and manner of people living in 1906. In typically Herring-family fashion, this was a group effort. Mark took the lead on the letter, Matilda and I worked on a fun little surprise to add to the letter. We can't wait for Mitchy to get his mail on the ship! October 1906 Our Dearest Mitchell How long has it been since we have seen you, our big man! You have been away from us so long, out to sea in the great unknown for what seems like an eternity. We hope and pray that all is well with you. We had quite a scare from the big earthquake. Your favorite restaurant the Pancake House is no longer, succumbed to a fire whose heat was hotter than hell itself. And how did that fire ravish our wonderful city, a wonderful place to be sure. We are all safe however; a little wiser on this wobbly land where we live and thankful to God for sparing us of any tragedy. The family is all doing well. Muffy is missing you terribly, but Layla and Muffin are up to such naughtiness that we’ve had to spank them almost daily. We heard from your grandparents in South Africa and they are having such a wonderful time on safari seeing animals that we have only seen in the zoo. Your sister Matilda is a wonderful help around the house and she has been sewing you some new clothes anticipating your speedy return. The black bear Molly that frequents our farm seems to be looking for you since we see her almost nightly. Your football team the Princeton Tigers are champions again having outscored their opponents 205-9. We know you long to be the quarterback, but you know your mother's heart will ache if those great shiny teeth of yours happened to be knocked out. The White Sox beat the Cubs in the world series, but I am sure that news would have reached you out in the ocean. Not sure if you met the Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen in port but he is trying to go to the South Pole. We only hope that you did not decide to join his expedition. We are missing you terribly, keep warm our big man and come home safely from the clutches of Neptune. Lovingly Mother, Father and Little Sister

item.title: Alabama Bound -- Roll Tide
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded:
When Tiffany went to Alabama last year I thought it would be easy to come and watch a football game. But, as anyone in the "know" would tell you football is big in the South! Needless to say, my idea to book a trip 3 weeks away from the game was not possible. Instead, I booked a ticked 9 months from the game.. and it took a while but I was able to go visit Tiffany and see Bama play.

Day 1 -- Thursday BBQ

I left the Bay Area pretty early and after a stopover in Chicago, I got into Birmingham around 3 pm and Tuscaloosa around 4 pm. All was going great until my GPS didn't take me to the hotel I thought I was staying at. When I booked I thought I booked the same hotel as last year -- Hampton Suites Tuscaloosa, but this time I booked Hampton Suites Tuscaloosa East.. How far is East from Campus.. oh only 1 minute but JET, or 20 minutes by car! What a dump! Oh yeah, dumps cost $350/night during football (only $59 outside of football). But I was here for some football.. but before football some BBQ. I picked Tiffany up and we went out for BBQ. I really love Dreamland! The waitress was a little funny.. she couldn't believe we just wanted Ribs with no sides! Also, I had a hard time ordering Sweet Tea (but unsweetened) She thought I was from Mars! After BBQ Tiffany gave me a grand tour of her new apartment and I got to meet her roommates.

Day 2 -- Student for a Day

Tiffany had class an I had work to do, but where to work? Well I headed to the biggest Starbucks on a campus and set up shop for all my calls and meetings. I just hung out with the students (I think I was the only one with gray hair!) What the photo could not capture was the noise level! I am sure my co-workers loved me. After class and work, we went for a walking tour to see all the sororities and their poms since it was Homecoming weekend -- Surprise! Each sorority made these boards out of rolled up tissue paper -- poms. We then went and had some dinner, watched some homecoming speeches and a huge bonfire. After dinner, Tiffany introduced me to the nightlife! Woah do I feel old! End of Day 2, low and behold this huge truck was parked at my hotel.  

Day 3 -- Game Day!

Since it was homecoming we got to see an amazing parade (sorry only took videos) but then it was off to tailgate. A few things to remember for game day for next time:
  1. Don't get run over by an RV: I have never seen so many RV's. They were streaming in and just on campus there were hundreds. I guess if the stadium seats 100,000 the people have to come from somewhere!
  2. Reserve Tailgating Spot: Every spot, every piece of grass was reservable. 20x20 squares with power and people brought in catering companies, tents (think wedding not camping), signs, and tons of beer!
  3. Dress up For Game Day: The girls (young to old) were dressed (makeup, high heels, pretty dresses, jewelry) for what would pass as evening cocktail attire in CA.
Tailgating with the fraternities: (Tiffany seems to know everyone!)   Game time! Roll Tide The game was fantastic, but what was even better was seeing my daughter growing up. She is so independent, so confident, seems to know everyone, and is having a blast. Keep it up, Tiffany!
